<F P=100> NEAR EAST/SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> INDIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Warns Against Repeal of Pressler Amendment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1112161893 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 11 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> BK1112161893 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] India today cautioned the United States that 
repealing the Pressler Amendment will legitimize Pakistan's 
clandestine nuclear weapons program. New Delhi also expressed 
concern that this will result in the delivery of the 
state-of-the-art F-16 aircraft to Pakistan, providing it with a 
greater number of delivery systems for weapons of mass 
destruction. 
  Speaking at a lunch hosted in honor of the visiting U.S. 
senators, including Mr. Pressler, the minister of state for 
external affairs, Mr. Salman Khurshid, pointed out that Pakistan 
already acknowledges possessing weapons of mass destruction. He 
said the U.S. Administration move will, therefore, destabilize 
the South Asian region. In such a scenario, India will need to 
reappraise its defense policies. 
  The minister objected to India being lectured on the human 
rights issue, especially in the light of a commitment to 
democratic norms. Mr. Khurshid said India is faced with a proxy 
war in Kashmir. He made it clear that motivated propaganda 
against India on human rights will be counterproductive. The 
U.S. senators--Mr. Pressler, Mr. Cochran, and Mr. Brown--are 
currently on a visit to several Asian countries. They will also 
hold talks with the prime minister, Mr. Narasimha Rao, and the 
home minister, Mr. Chavan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

