<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Ministry Welcomes Kazakhstan's Decision on NPT </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1612145593 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1423 GMT 16 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD1612145593 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Aleksandr Krylovich and </F>
Vladimir Taranov] 
  [Text] Moscow December 16 TASS -- ``Russia together with 
other countries is welcoming the decision of the Supreme Soviet 
of Kazakhstan to join the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty [NPT] 
as a member state not possessing nuclear weapons,'' Russian 
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Grigoriy Karasin said at a briefing 
today. 
  Thus, Kazakhstan's joining of the system of commitments 
based 
on the START-1 treaty and the 1992 Lisbon protocol has been 
completed from the legal point of view. ``Russia regards this 
step taken by Kazakhstan as a major contribution to the 
strengthening of the nuclear non-proliferation regime and to the 
ensuring of the nuclear arms reduction,'' he said. This is 
especially important now, because the non-proliferation regime 
has been jeopardized by the dangerous stand, taken by Ukraine. 
  According to Karasin, Russia would like to hope that the 
resolution, adopted by the Kazakh parliament, will set a good 
example for Ukraine. Whether an impetus will be given to the 
spreading of nuclear weapons all over the planet, or whether the 
mechanism of significant nuclear arms reductions, envisaged by 
the START-1 and START-2 treaties, will be set into motion, 
depends very much on the policy pursued by Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

