<H3> <TI>   Institute Plans Increased Control Over Nuclear Materials </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1012213693 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1806 GMT 10 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD1012213693 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Bakina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow December 10 TASS -- The ``Kurchatov 
Institute'' Russian scientific center has accomplished a draft 
of a new system of control over nuclear materials, Academician 
Nikolay Ponomarev-Stepnoy, vice-president of the center, told a 
news conference here today. 
  ``The law enforcement bodies of Russia have registered some 
cases of misappropriations of atomic materials lately,'' the 
researcher said. ``Although no such facts have been recorded 
directly at the `Kurchatov Institute,' the situation is very 
dangerous. We consider it necessary to strengthen control over 
nuclear materials, and a new draft of the control system has 
been worked out exactly for this purpose,'' the academician 
noted. 
  According to Aleksandr Rumyantsev, one of the main think 
tanks of the draft system, at present control over nuclear 
materials is based on data from the institute's accounts 
department. In the future the emphasis will be made on the 
results of physical measurements of materials which will allow 
to know a specific situation practically every week. At the 
same time the administration of the scientific center intends to 
take stock of nuclear products on a regular basis. 
  The draft of a new control system has been prepared together 
with specialists from the American Technical Institute (U.S.A.). 
Researchers from the ``Kurchatov Institute'' find it rather 
important that for the first time the Russian state scientific 
center has been closely cooperating with the U.S. private 
scientific establishment. 

</TEXT>

