<H3> <TI>   IAEA Team Given `All Information' on Chernobyl AES </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1412212993 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2052 GMT 14 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD1412212993 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By UKRINFORM correspondent Valentin Vernodubenko] </F>
  [Text] Kiev December 14 TASS -- A team of IAEA experts 
headed by Deputy IAEA General Director Morris Rosen has spent 
two days at the Chernobyl power plant. 
  Rosen told UKRINFORM they came to the plant as the 
international community is concerned with its work, including 
the functioning of the fourth power unit under sarcophagus. 
Another reason is international assistance to Chernobyl. In 
his words, the team was given all information about the plant 
operation. 
  Asked about the IAEA attitude to the on-going operation of 
RBMK reactors at Russian and Lithuanian nuclear power plants, 
Rosen said there is certain concern. However, they know about 
the situation at plants with RBMK reactors and did not have 
enough information about Chernobyl after the Ukrainian 
parliament decided to halt the plant. 
  ``We are interested in enhanced safety of the Chernobyl 
nuclear power plant and in giving the international public 
objective information on its current state. In February a new 
IAEA team will come to the plant to fully estimate the 
situation,'' Chernobyl nuclear power plant's general director 
Nikolay Sorokin told UKRINFORM. 

</TEXT>

