<H3> <TI>   Reports of Increased Americium Threat Dismissed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0601180894 Kiev KIEVSKIYE VEDOMOSTI in Russian 4 Jan 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> WS0601180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev KIEVSKIYE VEDOMOSTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vladimir Shunevich: ``Americium Is not as Black </F>
as It's Painted''] 
  [Text] Reports disseminated by Russian scientist B. 
Kopeykin and domestic and foreign media, claiming that 
americium-241, which was discovered after the Chernobyl 
breakdown, is far more dangerous than cesium, strontium, and 
plutonium, were the reasons behind a press conference held 
recently at the Ministry for Chernobyl Issues. The reports also 
indicated that measures applied after the Chernobyl catastrophe 
should be reexamined, including the possibility of evacuating 
certain districts of Kiev. 
  In the opinion of B. Prister, first deputy minister for 
Chernobyl issues, who headed the press conference, as well as of 
other Ukrainian specialists and scientists, the reports on the 
americium threat are groundless. Studies have shown that the 
volume of this element--which was discovered in 1944--does not 
exceed previous readings. Compared with cesium, strontium, or 
plutonium, its contribution to the radioactive pollution is 
insignificant, however, whereas the radioactivity of cesium and 
strontium will be gradually decreasing, the radioactivity of 
americium and other elements will increase. Nevertheless, 
according to our scientists, even when the maximum radiation 
level of americium is reached, which will be by the year 2050, 
its concentration in the Dnepr river will be so low, that this 
will be an exclusively scientific problem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

