<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL </F>
<F P=101></F>
<H3> <TI>     Indian Minister on Talks With Pakistan, Ties With U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1712145393 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1430 
GMT 17 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> BK1712145393 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] India has expressed the hope that the foreign 
secretary-level talks with Pakistan in the first week of next 
month will be successful and lead to a movement forward. 
Addressing the Consultative Committee Meeting of members of 
parliament attached to his ministry, the minister of state for 
external affairs, Mr. R.L. Bhatia, described as untrue the 
observation that the Simla agreement has not been functional. 
Mr. Bhatia reiterated India's total commitment to human rights 
and stated that the Human Rights Commission Bill has been 
introduced in parliament. 
  Regarding declaration of Pakistan as a terrorist state, Mr. 
Bhatia said that all requisite evidence available with India has 
been passed on to the United States. The U.S. has not taken the 
final step for its own reasons. 
  On Indo-U.S. relations, Mr. Bhatia allayed the apprehensions 
of the members and asserted that New Delhi will not compromise 
country's sovereignty and its independent position under 
pressure. He said India has explained its point of view 
frequently in detail and will continue to do so. He also said 
India's position on nonproliferation is very clear and based on 
sound and fundamental principles. 

</TEXT>

