<H3> <TI>     Bonn Said To Continue to Arm Indonesia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601192794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1733 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Schwerin (DDP/ADN) -- According to information in 
the SCHWERINER VOLKSZEITUNG newspaper, the Federal Government 
will continue to arm the Indonesian Navy. Parallel to the 
decision to deliver 39 former warships from the NVA [National 
People's Army of the former GDR] to the highly indebted 
island-state, the Federal Security Council has also approved the 
export of a 209 class submarine. Bonn has also given the green 
light for the options for the construction of two further 
submarines. The article is based on Bonn's response to a 
question from SPD [Social Democratic Party] Bundestag deputies 
on arms deals with Indonesia, the paper writes (Friday edition). 
  The submarines, each of which costs 665.1 million German 
marks, are covered by the Hermes government export credit 
guarantee. At the same time, the Federal Government has 
admitted that, contrary to previous statements, it has only 
partially demilitarized the former NVA ships or has supplied 
them as complete weapons systems to the Indonesian Navy, it is 
further reported. Sixteen ``Parchim'' ships have thus been 
handed over to the Indonesian Navy in a fully-equipped state. 
The delivery of the 39 NVA ships has also been guaranteed to 
the tune of 689.9 million German marks. 

</TEXT>

