<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mexican Authorities Deny ETA Directing Operations There </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA3012044093 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2329 GMT 29 Dec 
93 </F>

<F P=103> PA3012044093 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 29 Dec (NOTIMEX) -- Mexican judicial 
authorities denied here today that there is any evidence to 
indicate that members of the separatist ETA [Basque Fatherland 
and Liberty] are operating in Mexico, as Spanish media reported. 
  The Attorney General's Office (PGR) has not received any 
reports or evidence about the presence of ETA members in Mexico 
to promote armed actions from this country. 
  Information obtained at the PGR indicated that if ETA 
members 
are found to be operating in the country, the appropriate 
authorities will investigate the situation. The PGR stated in a 
communique that neither the Mexican judicial authorities nor 
Interpol have been asked by any Spanish authority to investigate 
the presence of members of the separatist organization. 
  Mexico conducts investigations with strict respect for the 
law, and the authorities do not allow themselves to be swayed by 
rumors that sometimes only confuse the public. 
  The Spanish newspaper ABC published a report stating that 
ETA 
members direct activities of that organization form Mexico and 
that they have infiltrated various sectors of the Mexican 
economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

