<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   7 January 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> HAITI </F>
<H3> <TI>   FRAPH Burns Over 200 Homes in Soleil; Radio Confirms 2 Dead </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2712213093 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2049 GMT 27 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> PA2712213093 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 27 Dec (EFE) -- More than 200 houses 
in Soleil neighborhood were burned today by members of the 
extreme right-wing "Front for Haiti's Advancement and Progress 
(FRAPH)" in an incident that produced at least several dead and 
injured. 
  FRAPH members, accompanied by soldiers in uniform, sought to 
"avenge" the murder of businessman Issa Paul, treasurer of their 
organization in Soleil. His burned body was found this morning. 
FRAPH members burned the houses of people they believe could be 
linked to Paul's murder. Although it is presumed that there are 
several dead as a result of the FRAPH attack, Haitian radio only 
confirmed two. Representatives of FRAPH, an organization that 
became public when the return of constitutional President 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide was being negotiated, even captured 
citizens. The soldiers in uniform did not intervene and 
appeared to be protecting FRAPH members, the radio reported. 
  FRAPH is made up of armed civilians, mostly former members 
of 
the Tonton Macoutes (paramilitary police) that existed during 
the Duvalier administration. 

</TEXT>

