<H3> <TI>   Citizens Rewarded for Information on Assassination Attempt </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2512175893 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1615 GMT 25 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> NC2512175893 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 25 Dec (MENA)--Interior Minister Hasan 
al-Alfi has stressed that whoever gives any information leading 
to the discovery of terrorists will be immediately rewarded. A 
small piece of information that may appear insignificant to 
citizens may lead to important positive results for the security 
agencies, he said. 
  Speaking after honoring three citizens who helped in the 
arrest of terrorist Sayyid Salah Sayyid Sulayman, who is 
suspected in the unsuccessful attempt to assassinate Prime 
Minister Dr. 'Atif Sidqi, the minister praised the positive 
contribution of the Egyptian public. He said that the 
successful efforts of security forces at this stage depend on 
cooperation from the public. 
  Al-Alfi said the enlightened Egyptian masses have realized 
that confronting the challenges facing the homeland requires 
unity against all criminal attempts against the security of the 
country and the safety of the citizens. 
  [In a Cairo-datelined report, Paris AFP in English at 1642 
GMT adds: "Three informers on Saturday shared a reward of 
$30,000 for the arrest of nine suspects in the attempted 
assassination of Egypt's Prime Minister 'Atif Sidqi."] 

</TEXT>

