<H3> <TI>   IDF Said To Call Off Hunt for Fatah Murderers </TI></H3>
<H4>   Under Agreement With Fatah </H4>
<F P=102> TA2412114993 Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST in English 24 Dec 
93 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> TA2412114993 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITIM] </F>
  [Text] The security forces have stopped hunting for Fatah 
fugitives in the Gaza District who murdered Israelis and 
Palestinians, under an agreement reached between senior Fatah 
leaders in the district and IDF [Israel Defense Forces] 
commanders in the region. 
  An IDF source confirmed the report, adding that it was 
forced 
upon the army, and that some IDF officers in the field are 
furious with the agreement. 
  At a meeting held two weeks ago, the two sides agreed the 
IDF 
would completely halt its pursuit of armed Fatah fugitives, 
including those known to have committed murder. According to 
the agreement, the IDF agreed there would be no active pursuit 
of these fugitives, but that if they happened to be caught, they 
would be arrested by the security forces. 
  It was agreed brothers 'Umar and Rajih Abu-Sittah, believed 
to have murdered, among others, Shaya Deutsch of Kfar Yam in 
Qatif Bloc last March, would have to hide in one place and not 
walk the streets. The IDF agreed not to pursue them despite the 
fact that they are suspected murderers. 

</TEXT>

