<F P=101> LIBYA </F>
<H3> <TI>   al-Qadhdhafi: `We Are Prepared To Clash' With West </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2912023593 Tripoli Libyan Television Network in Arabic 
2010 GMT 28 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD2912023593 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli Libyan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Speech by Colonel Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi from his motorcade </F>
in al-'Ujaylat on 28 December--recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Qadhdhafi] In the name of God, O sons of 
al-'Ujaylat, sons of Hamid and Rashid [not further identified]. 
O you who belonged to the movements of the companions [not 
further identified] and owned this land for more than 500 years. 
[passage omitted] 
  O brothers, the Westerners made a terrible mistake when they 
insisted on turning the Lockerbie problem into a political 
issue. If they had thought, if they had learned from lessons, 
they would not have fallen onto that dangerous, slippery path. 
They should have left the Lockerbie case a purely legal issue. 
Then they might have been able to try the suspects, to save 
their shameless faces. They might have been able to avoid the 
pothole they have fallen into if they had not made it a 
political issue. [passage omitted condemning France for 
following U.S.] 
  We are prepared to engage in battle with the imperialists. 
We held up the olive branch, asked for friendship, asked for 
understanding, asked for a peaceful settlement, asked for mutual 
reconciliation and asked for friendship and amity to prevail 
between the peoples, yet, the colonialist and imperialist 
circles are bent on confrontation and clashes. We are for it. 
We are prepared. O America, O France, O Britain, we are 
prepared for the confrontation. We are prepared to clash. 
[passage omitted] 
  We reject any infringement of our sovereignty, any harm to 
our citizens and any violation of our national law. Libyan law 
is above the law of the United Nations. Libyan law is above 
international law, because it concerns Libya's sovereignty and 
its right to live freely on its territory. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

