<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commando Group Claims Responsibility for Death of CDU MP 18 
Dec </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012171493 Hamburg DPA in German 1522 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3012171493 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Karlsruhe (DPA) -- A group called "27 June Movement 
-- Georg von Rauch Commando" has claimed responsibility for the 
fatal car accident of the Hesse CDU [Christian Democratic Union] 
politician Bernhard Saelzer on 18 December. The federal 
prosecutor's office announced today in Karlsruhe, in response to 
an inquiry, that it has started investigations into persons 
unknown suspected of setting up a terrorist organization and 
supporting the terrorist Red Army Faction (RAF). 
  In a letter claiming responsibility, which was made 
available 
to WIESBADENER TAGBLATT, it said: "It was no accident, even 
though it looked like one. We manipulated his Mercedes 300 SE 
in such a way that it was impossible to tell what caused 
Saelzer's accident despite the most thorough of examinations." 
  On 27 June this year, the operation aimed at finding the RAF 
members Wolfgang Grams and Birgit Hogefeld took place in Bad 
Kleinen. Georg von Rauch was shot in December 1971 in west 
Berlin during the search for members of the Baader-Meinhof 
group, the predecessor of the RAF. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

