<F P=100> NOTE TO SUBSCRIBERS: FAX SERVICE </F>
<H3> <TI>   NOTE TO SUBSCRIBERS: FAX SERVICE </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  111111 </F>
<F P=103> 111111 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  Subscribers who do NOT receive the Terrorism Rerport 
on-line can now sign up for our fax service. This service is 
designed to provide "paper" subcribers with time-sensitive, 
high-interest reports via fax. If you would like to be placed on 
the fax customer list, please provide the following information: 
  --Organizations, countries, topics, or incidents that you 
need to cover on a priority basis. Please be specific. 
--Recipients' titles or positions, name of office, voice phone 
number(s) and fax number. 
  You may phone in this information directly to the FBIS 
Terrorism Desk at (703) 733-5512, or fax it to (703) 437-8248 or 
(703) 733-5974. 
<H5>  HIGHLIGHTS </H5>
  Editor's Note: The FBIS Terrorism Desk welcomes 
suscribers' comments and suggestions at (703) 733-5512. 
  Highlights and major incidents in this edition of 
the Terrorism Report include: 
<H5>  Colombia/U.S. </H5>
  One of the Ecuadoran policemen abducted by the 
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) on 17 December 
reports that his kidnappers mistook his river patrol squad for 
U.S. DEA agents. 
<H5>  Egypt </H5>
  The Islamic Group has taken credit for attacking a tour 
bus and wounding 9 Austrians in Cairo on 27 December. 
<H5>  Germany </H5>
  The "27 June Movement -- Georg von Rauch Commando" has 
claimed responsibility for the 18 December car accident that 
killed Hesse CDU [Christian Democratic Union] politician 
Bernhard Saelzer. 
<H5>  India </H5>
  INDIAN EXPRESS newspaper carries an expose on immigration 
and customs security lapses in Punjab and Bombay. 
<H5>  Iran/France </H5>
  A Paris judge jailed Iranians Mojlabi Mashady and Hossein 
Yazdan Seta for "complicity with murder in relation with 
terrorist activities." LE POINT's article details the 
investigation results. 
<H5>  Iran/Greece </H5>
  An Italian newspaper reports that "important figures" from 
the the Greek "17 November" group went to Tehran for secret 
talks in mid-November. The report calls the visit "the first 
step toward" 17 November attacks on Western targets. 
<H5>  Peru </H5>
  The Maoist group Shining Path is blamed for six bombings 
between 26 and 30 December. December 31 marks the centennial of 
Mao Ze Dong. 
<H5>  Russia </H5>

  Four men kidnapped a group of children for a $10 million 
ransom in Rostov-on-Don, beginning a chase that ended in their 
arrest in Dagestan. As of 30 December, no political motive for 
the kidnapping had been ascertained. 
<H5>  Sudan/U.S. </H5>
  "Sudanese diplomatic sources" have characterized an awards 
ceremony conducted by the U.S. Embassy in Khartoum as a 
"provocation," but said that the Sudanese Government "does not 
want to respond." 
<H5>  Turkey </H5>
  In an interview with state television, the interior 
minister said that Kurdish Workers Party (PKK) leader Ocalan 
"might have been killed or wounded" in Syria. 
  A National Liberation Front of Kurdistan (ERNK) 
representative told a German magazine that "tourism is a very 
serious target for us. The actions will begin in spring with 
utmost determination. No one should go to Turkey." 
<H5>  SELECTED VIDEO REPORTS </H5>
  The following list includes terrorism-related video 
reports extracted from FBIS Video Program Summaries from 23 to 
29 December, ordered alphabetically by country. Each entry is 
prefaced by the name of the city where the report originated, 
followed by the FBIS TV Center order number (e.g., BOG 93-001) 
and the date of broadcast. Tapes may be ordered by calling 
1-800-822-5115 for subscribers in Virginia and 1-800-542-8660 
for those outside Virginia. Tapes are available for 30 days and 
are for U.S. Government official use only. 
<H5>  China/Taiwan </H5>
  Madrid MAD 93-357, Moscow MRT 93-504, Moscow MOS 93-5955 
and Algiers ALG 93-359 (28 Dec)--Couple hijacks plane to Taiwan; 
10th this year. 
<H5>  Egypt </H5>

  Havana HAV 93-335 (28 Dec) and Paris PAR 93-712 and 714 
(27 Dec)--Reports on bomb thrown at Austrian tourist bus in 
Cairo. 
  Algiers ALG 93-359 (28 Dec)--Report on attack on Cairo 
jewelry shop (fundamentalists suspected). 
  Johannesburg JOH 93-477 (28 Dec)--"Extremists" kill three 
in Cairo (1 min). 
