<F P=100> EAST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soldiers Threaten UN Troops; Canadians Held Several Hours </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0601195694 Paris AFP in English 1930 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0601195694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Jan 6 (AFP) -- Four Canadian peacekeepers 
were disarmed and held for several hours by Croatian soldiers 
who threatened the UN troops with their weapons, the UN 
Protection Force (UNPROFOR) announced Thursday. 
  General Jean Cot, the French soldier who commands UNPROFOR 
in 
the former Yugoslavia, described the incident Wednesday [5 
January] as "outrageous" and demanded that the Croatian soldiers 
be punished. 
  The Canadian troops had obtained a routine authorisation to 
cross Croatian lines in the Medak enclave in the south of the 
country. 
  Seven Croatian army soldiers approached them and ordered 
them 
to lay down their weapons before the Canadian soldiers were led 
away at gunpoint. 
  UNPROFOR said the four were released after negotiations with 
a local Croatian commander. 
  Canada has 560 troops in the region based at Gracac. They 
were deployed in the Medak area after Croatian troops attacked 
Serb villages, massacring dozens of people. 

</TEXT>

