<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombian Commander Says Venezuelans Arming ELN, FARC </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0701035394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0701035394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Miriam Ortiz from the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Charges leveled by a guerrilla from Arauca on the 
"24 Hours" newscast have confirmed that there is clandestine 
arms trafficking by the Venezuelan Guard to guerrillas of the 
ELN [Army of National Liberation] and the FARC [Revolutionary 
Armed Forces of Colombia] in the border area. On 5 January, the 
commander of the Army confirmed this information and said he had 
already given the Venezuelan authorities a list of names of 
Venezuelan soldiers involved in this illegal arms trade. 
  [Begin Army Commander General Hernan Jose Guzman recording, 
identified by caption] The operation we carried out and the 
statements of a guerrilla member produced information that was 
turned over to the Prosecutor's Office. If you want names, I can 
tell you that I cannot reveal them because this case is now the 
responsibility of the Venezuelan authorities. [end recording] 
  The "24 Hours" newscast, however, learned that the following 
Venezuelan soldiers are involved: Colonel Montes, Guard 
Escalante, and Inspectors Ramos and Nunez. We also learned that 
the Venezuelan Government is investigating certain reports that 
many Venezuelan soldiers and guards offer protection to 
Colombian guerrillas. Gen. Guzman also confirmed that there are 
constant exchanges between Venezuelan subversives and Colombia's 
ELN. 
  [Begin Guzman recording] We know that certain guerrillas, 
especially those in the ELN, have crossed the border to give 
training on the Venezuelan side. [end recording] 
  The Army commander added that although it is impossible to 
control the 2,219 km borderline, the necessary measures were 
implemented in coordination with the Venezuelan Army. 

</TEXT>

