<F P=101> PERU </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Insurgent Activities 17-19 Dec </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY3112230093 </F>
<F P=103> PY3112230093 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following are reports on insurgent 
activities in Peru compiled from Peruvian papers monitored 
between 17 and 19 December. 
  A group of 12 Shining Path "terrorists" stormed a bank in 
Lima and opened fire at point blank range against the seven 
employees and some 12 clients who were there, killing five 
people. A "terrorist" identified as Teodora Huamani Ramos also 
died during the incident. The "terrorists" escaped after 
scattering leaflets and planting two bombs on Riva Aguero 
Avenue, and one on Tranquilino Velarde Street. Another two 
groups of "terrorists" keeping watch outside the bank 
machine-gunned a police pickup truck that went past the bank, 
killing two plainclothesmen. (Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 17 
Dec 93 p A18) 
  On 16 December a group of approximately 60 Shining Path 
"terrorists" invaded the township of Chingal, in Sihuas 
Province, 270 km north of the city of Huaraz, burning public 
buildings and threatening to kill local authorities if they did 
not resign their posts within 15 days. (Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 
18 Dec 93 p A17) 
  On 14 December a group of nearly 60 Shining Path 
"terrorists" 
invaded Quinches District, in Sihuas Province, 310 km southeast 
of the city of Huaraz, where they first threatened to kill the 
local mayor and then later hung him from a tree in the Plaza de 
Armas. The "terrorists" stole money, food, animals, and 
medicines during the two days they stayed in the township. 
(Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 19 Dec 93 p A19) 

</TEXT>

