<H3> <TI>   Libyan Oppositionist Comments on Security in Cairo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0101142294 Cairo AL-WAFD in Arabic 23 dec 93 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC0101142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-WAFD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Abd-al-Nabi 'Abd-al-Sattar] </F>
  [Text] Muhammad Fa'iz Jibril, representative of the 
National Front for the Salvation of Libya in Cairo, has 
disclosed serious details about the position of the Libyan 
opposition elements in Egypt before and after the normalization 
of Egyptian-Libyan relations. In exclusive statements to 
AL-WAFD, Jibril affirmed that following the restoration of ties 
between Egypt and Libya, Libyan President Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi 
pledged not to touch his opponents in Cairo. 
  Jibril noted that the Egyptian authorities had relaxed 
protection measures around Libyan opposition elements residing 
in Egypt upon the normalization of relations with Libya in view 
of al-Qadhdhafi's pledge. He pointed out that Egypt and other 
Arab and European states have rejected the Libyan authorities' 
request to hand over the opponents of al-Qadhdhafi's regime. 
  Jibril noted that he has received many death threats 
involving him and other figures of the Libyan opposition and 
their families. He said that al-Qadhdhafi's regime has been 
involved in 23 attacks against Libyan opposition elements in 
European capitals. 
  He estimated the number of political prisoners in Libya at 
3,000 and affirmed that the Libyan opposition is closely 
monitoring developments in the case of the disappearance of 
[former Libyan foreign minister] Mansur al-Kikhya through daily 
contacts with the Egyptian authorities. 

</TEXT>

