<H3> <TI>   Tourism Minister Tallies Tourism Losses Due to Terrorism </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0501201294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1750 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0501201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Cairo, 5 Jan (MENA)--Minister of Tourism Dr. 
Mamduh al-Biltaji has expressed optimism about the future of 
tourism in Egypt. [passage omitted] 
  At a meeting with a visiting U.S. Congressional delegation 
today, he reviewed the Tourism Ministry's future policy to 
revive tourism in Egypt, especially from the United States as an 
important tourism export market. 
  Speaking about Egypt's losses due to terrorism, he said 
Egypt 
has incurred losses at all levels. He added that these 
incidents have sharply and directly deepened the tourism crisis 
in Egypt. He noted that the number of tourists decreased from 
3.2 million in 1992 to 2.2 million as of October in 1993. 
Tourist nights decreased from about 20 million to around 13 
million as of October 1993 and tourism revenues dropped from 
$2.3 billion in 1992 to $1.1 billion as of October 1993. He 
pointed out that these statistics are serious indications as to 
the severity of the crisis. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

