<F P=102>  LD3012180193 Hamburg DPA in German 1714 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3012180193 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cologne [no date as received] (DPA) -- Heribert 
Hellenbroich, former president of the Office for the Protection 
of the Constitution [Bundesverfassungsschutz], views the letter 
claiming responsibility [for the death of Christian Democratic 
Union politician Bernhard Saelzer] as "a bad joke perpetrated by 
amateurs." [see item LD3012171493 in previous Terrorism Report] 
He told Friday's edition of the Cologne daily EXPRESS that the 
writers had made three decisive mistakes which had unmasked 
them: "First, the letter is very different from the confused 
linguistic style of the Red Army Faction [RAF]. Second, real 
terrorists would never claim to have tampered with the victim's 
car. They act professionally and do not talk about it. And 
third, they look for symbolic figures for their attacks. Mr. 
Saelzer was neither well known nor powerful enough to be a 
target for terrorists." 

</TEXT>

